WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.560
Okay, thank you very much.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:13.840
Welcome to the Quarto session, and I have the distinct pleasure of talking about things

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:18.200
that look like a stack of crepes, but actually they're manuscripts.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:22.400
So today I'm going to be talking about reproducible manuscripts with Quarto.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:28.959
So I want to talk a little bit about the full sort of spectrum of complexity of reproducible

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:30.559
scientific projects.

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:32.320
What do I mean by that?

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.480
Majority of my time as an educator particularly, and an educator who tends to teach students

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:42.400
who are learning computing for the first time and does so with Quarto, I live in this wonderful

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:43.400
land.

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:45.439
It is a fantastic place to be.

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:47.520
You have a single Quarto document.

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:51.080
You are sort of like coding in one language because that's the language we're teaching

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:55.520
the students, and we have full control over sort of like everything that they're doing,

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.320
including the tools that they're using to write their code.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:03.320
And the type of things that they're producing, while quite in-depth for them, are things

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:07.720
that where the code can all live in a single file, and they don't mind running it over

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.120
and over again with each edit.

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:10.120
You want to change a header?

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:11.120
Fine.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.800
Let's just run the whole compute again, and things go pretty fast and pretty neatly.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:20.239
And we tend to get HTML outputs as a result, and we can publish them on the web.

00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:24.680
While that's like a majority of the time I'm living and breathing, the rest of the time

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:29.360
I am thinking about, well, we collect data from these students about how they learn.

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:32.000
At some point, we're going to want to publish these results.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.160
So how do we go from the simplest case to things that get sort of progressively more

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:38.160
complex?

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.760
So from simplest to let's go to simple.

00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:45.480
We can again have a document, a single Quarto document with just some R code in it, and

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:51.320
with the help of the Quarto journal articles extension, I can output things to PDF or Word,

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:56.879
not just output to any PDF or Word, but a document that looks exactly like the document

00:01:56.879 --> 00:02:02.279
in the journals I'm submitting my manuscripts to expect them to look like.

00:02:02.279 --> 00:02:07.080
But again, the code in here is sort of, I'm going to say simple enough.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:11.919
That's not to say the analyses are very simplistic, but to say that I'm okay re-rendering this

00:02:11.919 --> 00:02:17.479
document every time I'm making edits to that, and this is a happy place to be too.

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:20.440
But science is rarely that simple.

00:02:20.559 --> 00:02:24.240
Typically, you're working with multiple collaborators, each with their favorite computing language

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:25.839
and code editor.

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:30.240
And you're in multiple stages of a project, each with their own level of feasibility of

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:33.479
what can be rerun with each edit and what needs to be cached.

00:02:33.479 --> 00:02:38.059
You don't want to be cleaning your data every time you want to change your headers for example.

00:02:38.059 --> 00:02:40.520
So a more complex project might look like this.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:45.720
Maybe you have a single Quarto document, but a bunch of notebooks and stuff laying around,

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:49.320
and maybe everyone's coding in R in your team, and you want to output to something like a

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.960
PDF or Word for a journal submission.

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:56.919
Or things can get even more exciting, where you have sort of the diversity of the tooling

00:02:56.919 --> 00:03:02.360
your collaboration team is using increases, where we have even more notebooks, where little

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:04.740
bits of the project are being done.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:09.199
Maybe we have now multiple QMD files, some of them running R code in them, and some of

00:03:09.199 --> 00:03:11.119
them running Python code in them.

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:15.839
But ultimately, we need to bring all of this together into a culminating manuscript that

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:18.960
we want to submit to a journal.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:24.919
We can, turns out, leverage the notion of Quarto projects for writing these fully reproducible

00:03:24.919 --> 00:03:26.880
scientific manuscripts.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:32.360
So I'm going to take an aside for a second and talk about a little bit of a mind shift

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:35.520
for some of you, and at least for myself as well.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:39.639
Whenever I use the word notebook, in my mind, I'm always thinking about like Jupyter notebooks

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:42.479
because the word notebook is in there.

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:46.639
But ultimately, a notebook is a document that contains both code and narrative.

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:50.240
So going forward, when I say notebook, I could be talking about a Jupyter notebook,

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.160
or I could be talking about a Quarto document, where you again see your code and narrative

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:55.759
in the same place.

00:03:55.759 --> 00:03:57.720
So let's keep that in mind.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.559
And think about what the current state of affairs is.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:04.960
Most computational science is born in notebooks, and it dies.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:06.619
That's sort of not so nice.

00:04:06.619 --> 00:04:09.520
Maybe ends in PDF or Word documents.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.320
And what happens in between is that we have peer review and publication workflows that

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:18.220
don't tend to support these notebooks as research outputs.

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:23.160
And these more complex scenarios that I talked about involve a lot of like manual finagling

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:24.160
at the end.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.279
And not in a devious way, but just at the end of the project, you're just trying to

00:04:28.279 --> 00:04:33.440
get it over the threshold to bring the project to this journal submission stage.

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:39.720
And it's during this process that oftentimes reproducibility is lost.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:43.320
Or at least take some sort of second seat to formatting requirements.

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:47.600
I will at least be honest and say that I have certainly done the thing where I had

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:53.839
this beautiful notebook that I got to 90% of what the journal wanted as a Word file.

00:04:53.839 --> 00:04:57.079
And then I manually edited that Word file.

00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:02.519
And then I put a footnote saying the code can be found in the GitHub repository.

00:05:02.519 --> 00:05:05.480
Choose your own adventure.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:11.799
And ultimately, the final submission that the journals want or archive once rarely captures

00:05:11.799 --> 00:05:12.799
all these computations.

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:16.279
I mean, sure, they'll happily take your supplementary documents.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:20.040
But they rarely archive those documents with your manuscript.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:23.200
And sometimes they're not necessarily even reachable.

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:26.519
So these can live in supplementary materials sometimes.

00:05:26.519 --> 00:05:31.880
And there is no ensuring that that GitHub repo I link to in my supplementary documentation

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:34.779
is going to be there a year or two years from now.

00:05:34.779 --> 00:05:39.119
So if you've tried to reproduce others' work so that you could learn from them and iterate

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:44.720
on it, you probably have had difficulty trying to sort of gather up all the pieces needed

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.959
as well.

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:51.359
So there is, you know, this is the current state of affairs.

00:05:51.359 --> 00:05:55.320
But also within the current state of affairs, there's lots of great minds thinking about,

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:56.720
well, how do we make this better?

00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:58.320
This is not a new problem.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:03.079
And there's been sort of like initiatives, various initiatives over at least my academic

00:06:03.079 --> 00:06:09.079
career of sort of trying to move reproducible computational science forward.

00:06:09.079 --> 00:06:13.679
And one of the sort of the current ongoing projects is this Notebooks Now project that's

00:06:13.679 --> 00:06:20.140
funded through this Sloan grant and a grant from the American Geophysical Union.

00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:25.579
And the idea is to try to sort of make these pieces work well.

00:06:25.579 --> 00:06:32.119
So what could a roadmap look like for fully reproducible scientific manuscripts that are

00:06:32.119 --> 00:06:36.799
not just PDFs that are the outputs of a single QMD file?

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:42.799
So what we need is one piece of the puzzle is we actually need an actual publishing workflow,

00:06:42.799 --> 00:06:47.760
an end-to-end scholarly publishing workflow, starting with that first notebook you started,

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:52.279
you know, iterating on when you have the idea for your project to the final manuscript that

00:06:52.279 --> 00:06:58.880
you produced that treats things like Jupyter and Quarto notebooks as the primary element

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:02.820
of scientific record, not just that PDF output.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:08.700
We also need a publication process that sort of elevates transparent and reproducible workflows

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:15.739
by authors where they are able to sort of bring together and submit and archive their

00:07:15.739 --> 00:07:19.320
software along with their document and their data.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:24.079
And this is going to take obviously lots of doing on the publisher's end, but it is putting

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:30.720
on a bunch of new work, good work, good scientific work, but new work on the authors as well.

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:35.859
So hopefully along with these initiatives come sort of new forms of credit to the folks

00:07:35.859 --> 00:07:38.359
who are working on this as well.

00:07:38.359 --> 00:07:43.079
I'm going to focus on the first two pieces of the puzzle where Quarto can provide technical

00:07:43.079 --> 00:07:48.239
solutions to that and maybe perhaps then provide bandwidth for others to work on the third

00:07:48.239 --> 00:07:50.059
piece of the puzzle as well.

00:07:50.059 --> 00:07:54.440
So with Quarto, it can be authored in your favorite code editor so you no longer need

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:58.200
to, you know, convince your collaborators to change their home.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:02.399
You can render QMD files or Jupyter notebooks to a variety of outputs.

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:05.140
You can execute code in R, Python, and more.

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:11.920
You can apply journal style to your outputs with these Quarto extensions and publish to,

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:16.519
you know, a variety of venues including GitHub Pages, Netlify, and more.

00:08:16.519 --> 00:08:22.679
Now last year I said all of these things at this conference and over the year I hope that

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:25.279
many of you have tried these things.

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:29.640
And with Quarto projects we know that we can sort of orchestrate this notion of multiple

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:31.839
inputs and multiple outputs.

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:38.760
Well now with a new project type, that's the manuscript project type, you can orchestrate

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:43.679
these multiple inputs and outputs again but you can also leverage this idea of embedded

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:46.739
computations that I'll talk to you about in a little bit.

00:08:46.739 --> 00:08:49.599
So let's introduce this new project type.

00:08:49.599 --> 00:08:55.000
This is Quarto 1.4 onward so there are pre-release versions available right now on the Quarto

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.159
website but it is not available yet on the release version.

00:08:59.159 --> 00:09:05.440
We can produce manuscripts in multiple formats and give readers an easy way to sort of peruse

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:10.799
them by creating a website that goes along with it and we can publish the computations

00:09:10.799 --> 00:09:16.640
so that readers can both sort of take a look at the computations and even go a step forward

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:20.119
hopefully and start interacting with the computations as well.

00:09:20.119 --> 00:09:22.559
So let's go ahead and write our manuscript.

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:26.400
You can start any of these Quarto projects in one of two ways.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:31.919
You can say well create an empty project for me either using the RStudio IDE is usually

00:09:31.919 --> 00:09:37.440
what I tend to do or you can use the command line interface and do something like Quarto

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:42.200
create project manuscript my favorite paper for example.

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:47.580
Or go to the Quarto documentation and grab one of the projects that we've already sort

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:52.039
of like prepared for you so that you can see all of the pieces working together and start

00:09:52.039 --> 00:09:56.760
replacing the bits of the narrative that don't relate to your work with your data

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:58.440
and your narrative.

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:05.559
And if you do this in a folder that is being tracked by Git and has a GitHub repository

00:10:05.559 --> 00:10:10.200
associated with it you can have pretty easy going with your publishing as well.

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:17.280
So with one command like Quarto publish you end up with a website that looks like this

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:19.460
for your manuscript.

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:24.500
So what we're seeing here is a variety of things that you would expect from a manuscript.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:31.419
We have figures that are actually cross-referenced and if I hover over these I can sort of see

00:10:31.419 --> 00:10:34.140
the cross-referenced figures as well.

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:39.219
I can see that the articles are the notebooks where the computation is happening is sort

00:10:39.219 --> 00:10:44.299
of linked on the side and one of my favorite things that's sort of like on by default is

00:10:44.539 --> 00:10:50.260
you can go ahead and start doing things like highlighting the text.

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:52.979
Oh come on.

00:10:52.979 --> 00:10:57.900
And also if you have you can set up a group with your collaborators and say something

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:02.260
like hey maybe we want to phrase these things slightly differently.

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:06.619
So this hypothesis feature is turned on and so you no longer have to just like be doing

00:11:06.619 --> 00:11:13.539
those PDF annotations you can start interacting with things in this way.

00:11:13.539 --> 00:11:17.419
Another thing is that from this one single source you get multiple formats.

00:11:17.419 --> 00:11:24.780
So on this rendered web page you can see that we're referencing to a PDF that has the AGU

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:28.400
format so has a journal format as well as a Word file.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:34.219
So starting with the same YAML of my project right I have one YAML that says I want to

00:11:34.219 --> 00:11:40.659
HTML, I want a PDF, I also want a Word file.

00:11:40.659 --> 00:11:47.260
I can actually get to this output where I'm able to see and access each of these formats.

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:50.400
In addition I get really rich front matter.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:54.020
So you're probably used to you know YAMLs that are a few lines long.

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:57.580
This is like a whole novel in and of itself this YAML.

00:11:57.580 --> 00:12:02.919
But the need for this is that some journals want some things and other journals want other

00:12:02.919 --> 00:12:07.140
things and it's nice to be able to sort of put everything on there.

00:12:07.659 --> 00:12:12.780
Each time you start a project you have a standard YAML that you fill with your collaborators

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:19.340
and if you're submitting to this journal then only the relevant pieces will be picked up

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:23.739
and rendered there and for the Word output that we were able to access from that home

00:12:23.739 --> 00:12:29.020
page again only the relevant pieces get picked up and fit in there as well.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:34.979
For the next bit I'm going to sort of show you a video of how we can actually not sort

00:12:34.979 --> 00:12:41.659
of break this paradigm of a single Corto file but also grab computations from notebooks

00:12:41.659 --> 00:12:42.659
as well.

00:12:42.659 --> 00:12:48.059
So I have a Corto file and the data set that goes with it as well and let's take a look

00:12:48.059 --> 00:12:50.380
at the contents of that Corto file.

00:12:50.380 --> 00:12:56.179
I'm housing all of that in the same folder as my manuscript and if I go ahead and render

00:12:56.179 --> 00:13:01.059
it you'll see that this particular notebook is not like my paper.

00:13:01.059 --> 00:13:06.940
It's just a few things I was trying, maybe one table or one figure I have created and

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:12.219
let's assume for a second that there was a lot of compute required to create one of these.

00:13:12.219 --> 00:13:20.140
Then I go to my main document, my manuscript, and I start using an embed shortcode to say

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:23.340
I'm not going to bring in that code chunk here.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:28.940
What I want to do is I want that code chunk to stay in my notebook but I'm going to embed

00:13:28.940 --> 00:13:30.979
it in my main manuscript.

00:13:30.979 --> 00:13:44.700
So I'm able to grab the label of that code chunk and link it here.

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:50.900
And let's go ahead and take a look to see that the table that we produced in our notebook

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:55.539
is embedded with a link that can take me back into the notebook as well.

00:13:55.539 --> 00:13:57.640
I had some R code in this document.

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:02.880
My main manuscript was a QMD and I embedded a QMD here as well.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:09.880
This is also a nice opportunity to show you some of the nice features of the visual editor

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:10.880
in RStudio.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:21.200
I'm able to create these cross references in a pretty straightforward manner and basically

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:23.760
include them in my paper.

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:28.919
Now let's imagine that while I am a person who likes to write code in R, I have a collaborator

00:14:28.919 --> 00:14:35.200
who has created this fantastic visualization in their Jupyter notebook using Python code.

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:40.239
So I've now received their notebook where they had already executed the code.

00:14:40.239 --> 00:14:46.359
And what I can do here is, again, I can now embed in the same QMD file output from that

00:14:46.359 --> 00:14:47.679
notebook as well.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:52.799
So I'm able to bring in outputs from different languages and different types of notebooks

00:14:52.840 --> 00:15:00.359
into the one manuscript file and not having to re-render that code again or re-execute

00:15:00.359 --> 00:15:06.320
that code again, but simply grab the results that were already created when my collaborator

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:08.520
made that visualization for me.

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:15.200
And I can, again, using the same syntax, using the same syntax, do a cross reference to that

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:16.200
as well.

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:18.880
So let's go ahead and convince ourselves that that actually works.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:23.960
If I scroll down, I have my lovely visualization made with Python.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:31.599
And let's pop that out.

00:15:31.599 --> 00:15:38.760
I can go to the QMD file and start interacting with that notebook, or I can go to the IPython

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:44.359
notebook and start interacting with that as well from this single document.

00:15:44.359 --> 00:15:47.960
So what is next after this?

00:15:48.039 --> 00:15:55.359
Well, what I demonstrated here is that you can start perusing the code, which is fantastic.

00:15:55.359 --> 00:15:57.960
And at times, that's perhaps all you need.

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:03.760
In fact, when I was first starting to play with the manuscripts feature, I was thinking,

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:08.599
I wish it would just pop out and let me take a look at it and then go back to its home.

00:16:08.599 --> 00:16:13.200
I want to convince myself as to how that figure was created, but maybe I'm going to focus

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:16.880
on reading this paper for the remainder of the time.

00:16:16.919 --> 00:16:22.719
When it comes time to actually perhaps taking somebody else's paper and saying, I really

00:16:22.719 --> 00:16:28.239
want to understand how they implemented this method or how they created this table, I might

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:31.080
want to genuinely dive into the code.

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:35.919
And sure, I could go to the supplementary information and go to their GitHub repo and

00:16:35.919 --> 00:16:38.200
clone that repo and get started.

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:41.520
But we know that there are a lot of hurdles along the way when you do that.

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:45.359
So I want to interact with that code in a computational environment that's just a click

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:50.599
away that has all the software and packages needed to reproduce the manuscript.

00:16:50.599 --> 00:16:57.039
In 2019, there was this article published in Nature where actually an article on eLife

00:16:57.039 --> 00:16:58.960
allowed you to do this.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:04.000
As of today, that article is paywalled, and you can't access the links anymore.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.760
And this is not to say the authors did anything wrong.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:12.680
It's to say it's been years, and this is very near and dear to a lot of scientists' hearts

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:15.839
problems that's really difficult to solve.

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:20.400
So I think with the manuscript feature with Corto, we're making advances into getting

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:21.400
there.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:26.239
So as of today, you can start kicking the tires on the Corto use binder feature, where

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:33.199
you can see in addition to these static outputs, you have a link to be able to launch a binder

