But we would love for you to sort of go in and take a look to see how this is working

00:17:43.359 --> 00:17:44.359
for you.

00:17:44.359 --> 00:17:47.040
Is it capturing everything that you need?

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:48.400
And is it working out for you?

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:50.520
And give us some feedback on that as well.

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:51.719
So where do you go from here?

00:17:51.719 --> 00:17:56.040
I would recommend rewind back to that get started and start again.

00:17:56.040 --> 00:18:02.040
And I would point you to the documentation for the Corto pre-release, where Charlotte

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:06.079
has actually created a wonderful repository that you can get started with.

00:18:06.079 --> 00:18:07.439
Thank you so much for listening.

00:18:07.439 --> 00:18:09.439
And I'd be happy to take questions.

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:12.040
I'm back.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:22.760
Thank you for the great presentation.

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:28.520
So I'm going to turn things real, real quick with one question.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:35.839
When we submit a manuscript, we often don't do it just once.

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:41.880
Do you have any tips for a workflow, like if you have to switch templates because you're

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:44.119
submitting to a different journal?

00:18:44.119 --> 00:18:51.119
And or resources slash ways to contribute to the pool of journal templates that are

00:18:51.119 --> 00:18:52.119
already available?

00:18:52.119 --> 00:18:53.119
Yeah.

00:18:53.119 --> 00:18:54.119
Wonderful.

00:18:54.119 --> 00:18:58.160
So it's actually that first bit is easier than you think.

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:02.599
And I know that we don't tend to write an article for multiple journals at the same

00:19:02.599 --> 00:19:03.599
time.

00:19:03.599 --> 00:19:07.479
So it generally tends to be iterative, where you maybe submit to one and then you try another.

00:19:07.479 --> 00:19:10.079
But you can add other templates here as well.

00:19:10.079 --> 00:19:15.079
So in this case, I only had on line 10 here one of the journal templates being used.

00:19:15.079 --> 00:19:17.479
But you can add other ones here as well.

00:19:17.479 --> 00:19:23.160
So I could have added something like PLOS PDF or JASA PDF and kept going.

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:28.719
And Corto will happily render all of them for you, grab the necessary bits of the YAML,

00:19:28.719 --> 00:19:31.319
and create those PDFs for you.

00:19:31.319 --> 00:19:35.680
There is a rich and growing sort of ecosystem of these extensions.

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:39.199
And I think the best way to contribute, if you have a journal you want to submit to,

00:19:39.199 --> 00:19:40.400
is grab one of the ones.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:47.319
There's actually a starter repo in that Corto journals templates organization as well.

00:19:47.319 --> 00:19:51.359
And start sort of like playing around with it.

00:19:51.359 --> 00:19:56.239
You may or may not, if you need a PDF output, you probably want to be sort of a little bit

00:19:56.239 --> 00:20:00.339
confident with writing a bit of like latex styling code.

00:20:00.339 --> 00:20:04.500
But I would also say that if you've started with a template for a journal of interest

00:20:04.500 --> 00:20:09.459
to you, but you're running into roadblocks, opening some issues and asking for help would

00:20:09.459 --> 00:20:10.459
be great as well.

00:20:10.459 --> 00:20:14.619
As the developers are often like watching that space and trying to help people get over

00:20:14.619 --> 00:20:15.619
that hurdle.

00:20:15.619 --> 00:20:16.619
Awesome.

00:20:16.619 --> 00:20:18.020
Thank you very much.

